Solid priorities for fragile states
LONDON/MONROVIA/KIGALI – No country has been spared the repercussions of COVID-19.
However, the world's most "fragile" states are facing a particularly complex set of challenges.
In fact, before the pandemic began, Yemen, Sudan, Haiti, Sierra Leone, Myanmar, Afghanistan, Venezuela and other countries were already grappling with poverty, conflicts, corruption and inadequate public administration.
Today, these factors leave these countries ill-equipped to manage the COVID-19 crisis.
What each country needs to get through the pandemic is precisely what fragile states lack: a functioning state apparatus capable of developing and implementing an action plan, an effective police force to enforce rules, social programs that provide funding, supplies, and health services to care for infected people.
The lack of state capacity is immediately felt in the field of public health.
While Europe has 4,000 intensive care beds per million inhabitants, several regions of Africa have only five per million inhabitants.
Mali has only three ventilators for the entire country.
An effective response also requires trust in the state's intervention.
However, in addition to its lack of resources, the public administration of most fragile states enjoys little public support.
In countries recovering from a conflict or suffering from endemic corruption, many people will be reluctant to support the government even if it proves capable of governing.
A strong private sector is also an essential component of effective and resilient states.
Citizens should be able to work in order to support their families and the state should be able to collect tax revenues in order to help those who cannot do so.
However, in fragile states, the formal economy is not present enough to meet these needs.
Earlier during the crisis, there was hope that some fragile states would avoid the worst health consequences of COVID-19 due to the demographic weight of the young population and geographic remoteness.
However, from our perspective as co-chairs of the new Council on State Fragility, it must be acknowledged that this was not the case.
In recent weeks, Sudan, South Sudan, Somalia and Yemen have all had infection and mortality rates rivaling those of developed countries that were hit by the coronavirus first.
Worse still, the economic consequences of the pandemic will certainly be more severe for fragile states. These will not only result from national lockdowns, but also from what is happening abroad.
Trade with countries like China has declined, remittances from expatriates have fallen, commodity prices and oil revenues have collapsed, and deficits are piling up.
Since fragile states rely on imports for most of their food, the terms "hunger" and even "famine" are being used more and more frequently.
We should now have understood that the problems of less developed countries are becoming mostly global issues, whether in the form of mass migrations, criminal or terrorist organizations, or economic repercussions.
Given that half of the disadvantaged populations will live in fragile states by 2030, these problems will continue to worsen.
This is why the Council on State Fragility has set as its absolute priority to draw attention to the specific challenges these countries must overcome.
The council, composed of former world leaders, ministers, diplomats, business personalities, academics, as well as heads of development organizations, will combine cutting-edge research with meticulous political knowledge. Its aim will be to guide national and international policymakers who will determine how fragile states will emerge from this crisis and who will tackle their broader and deeper problems.
Decentralization, adaptability, and the prudent use of data will be essentials.
For example, it is widely proven that "targeted lockdowns" of local outbreaks are often more appropriate than national lockdowns.
Such knowledge could prove crucial for fragile states.
However, we must act quickly before the critical phase of the pandemic in the West comes to an end and the sense of urgency dissipates.
We propose five recommendations.
First, access to social protection must be simpler and faster.
Sometimes, this will mean universal eligibility rather than precise targeting.
Mobile phone networks should be used to gather information on immediate needs and to provide regular small payments (although for a limited duration).
Second, national food production should be encouraged.
For example, Sierra Leone, which used to grow rice, has become increasingly dependent in recent decades.
More generally, Africa accounts for 60% of the world's unused arable land.
Local production initiatives for staple crops must be rapidly scaled up to a much larger extent.
Thirdly, once vaccine production begins, the international community must ensure that fragile states are not excluded from the market by wealthier countries.
When the threat is a contagious pathogen, no country is safe unless all are.
We must advocate for and accelerate the production of multiple vaccines in order to ensure rapid and widespread distribution.
Fourthly, businesses in fragile states need immediate assistance.
As noted by the most involved financial institutions in international development; small businesses in less developed countries are often neglected and suffer the negative consequences of broader goals and rules (since it is easier to achieve a goal by investing in large projects in larger economies).
Nevertheless, it is precisely these small businesses that need more significant investments.
Finally, the G20 should do more to support highly indebted fragile states that are forced to choose between paying their foreign creditors or saving their population.
It is expected that countries receiving bilateral development aid will have to repay about 40 billion dollars to private and public creditors this year alone.
In order to prevent this financial shock, we urge all G20 members to temporarily suspend accumulated debts not only until next year, but also until the end of the crisis.
Furthermore, it is crucial that all fragile states receive emergency financing to support their efforts to contain COVID-19 and mitigate its economic impacts — particularly countries that usually do not have access to financing from the World Bank or the International Monetary Fund.
COVID-19 will exacerbate existing problems in all fragile states around the world.
However, if the international community reacts promptly, we can mitigate the worst impacts of the pandemic.
If there is one lesson to be learned from this crisis, it is that livelihoods and lives will be saved if we move faster than the virus.
